text=[[!DocumentationToDo]]ÀŠÀŠ->%note% TODO:  This page needs to be cleaned up for 2.0 release.ÀŠÀŠSee also the MarkupMasterIndex.ÀŠÀŠPmWiki uses the markup sequence [@(:directive ...:)@] for a number of directives and text substitutions.  Many of these replace the "double-bracket" directives that were used in PmWiki 1.0 and earlier versions.  Here's a brief description of each.ÀŠÀŠ[[#title]][@(:title text:)@]ÀŠ->Sets a page's title to be something other than the name of the page.  For example, the markupÀŠÀŠ    [=(:title Patrick's home page:)=]ÀŠÀŠ->uses "Patrick's home page" as the title of the page in the browser title bar (HTML <title> tag) and the title area of the page ($PageTitle variable).  Note that apostrophes and other special characters can be used here.ÀŠÀŠ[[#keywords]][@(:keywords word, ...:)@]ÀŠ->Sets page keywords in an HTML @@<meta name='keywords' content='word, ...' />@@ tag.ÀŠÀŠ[[#description]][@(:description A page about ...:)@]ÀŠ->Sets page description in an HTML @@<meta name='description' content='A page about...' />@@ tag.ÀŠÀŠ[[#comment]][@(:comment This won't be displayed:)@]ÀŠ->Allows comments to be included in the page markup without them being visible in the displayed page.  This may be useful for providing editing guidance to new users, among other uses.ÀŠÀŠ[[#include]][@(:include PageName:)@] and [@(:include PageName#start#end:)@]ÀŠ->Includes the contents of another page into the text of the current page.  The second form of the include is used to include only the portion of the page between the #start and #end anchors.  #start and #end can be numeric, in which case they refer to line numbers within the page, so that [@(:include RecentChanges#1#10:)@] grabs only the first ten lines of the RecentChanges file. ÀŠ->See IncludeOtherPagesÀŠÀŠ->In PmWiki 2, one can specify a range of lines to be used in theÀŠ->[@(:include:)@] directive, thus:ÀŠÀŠ->(from Pm email)ÀŠÀŠ->[@(:include SomePage :)@] - include all of `SomePage\\ÀŠ[@(:include SomePage lines=10 :)@] - include lines 1-10 of `SomePage\\ÀŠ[@(:include SomePage lines=1..10 :)@] - include lines 1-10 of `SomePage\\ÀŠ[@(:include SomePage lines=6..10 :)@] - include lines 6-10 of `SomePage\\ÀŠ[@(:include SomePage lines=6.. :)@] - include lines 6 to end of `SomePage\\ÀŠ[@(:include SomePage lines=6..6:)@] - include only line 6 of `SomePageÀŠÀŠÀŠ[[#noheader]][@(:noheader:)@],ÀŠ[[#nofooter]][@(:nofooter:)@], ÀŠ[[#notitle]][@(:notitle:)@],ÀŠ[[#nogroupheader]][@(:nogroupheader:)@],ÀŠ[[#nofootheader]][@(:nofootheader:)@],ÀŠetc.ÀŠ->These directives disable the header, footer, and page title portions of a page's layout (if the page's skin allows it).ÀŠÀŠ[[#spacewikiwords]][@(:(no)spacewikiwords:)@]ÀŠ->Turns on (off) automatic spacing of bare WikiWords within the page text.  When on, `WikiWord will be displayed as "Wiki Word".ÀŠÀŠ[[#linkwikiwords]][@(:(no)linkwikiwords:)@]ÀŠ->Turns on (off) automatic linking of bare WikiWords to pages of the same name.ÀŠÀŠ[[#if]][@(:if cond param:)@]ÀŠ->The [@(:if cond param:)@] syntax allows portions of the markup text to be conditionally processed (up to the next [@(:if:)@]) depending on administrator-defined conditions.  The predefined conditions are "true", "false", "group", and "name".  For example, ÀŠ-->[@(:if group PmWiki:)This text displays only in the PmWiki group(:if:)@]ÀŠ->For more details, see [[ConditionalMarkup]]. ÀŠÀŠ[[#pagelist]][@(:pagelist group=xxx fmt=yyy list=zzz:)@]ÀŠ->The [@(:pagelist ..:)@] syntax allows to include a bulleted list of pagenames which are within the specified group. The group and pagenames are displayed as links.ÀŠÀŠ:::[@group=xxx@]: optional, xxx = name of group, which pages should be included in the listÀŠÀŠ--->%green%Q: can you specify pages as well, e.g via regex or matching name-prefix: Group\.PREF.* = all pages of group "Group" starting with "PREF" ÀŠ--->A:%Pm% No, just groups and not pages.  There may be a new option added at some point that allows specifying fullnames by regex.  Plus there's always the [@list=zzz@] option below which ''does'' allow arbitrary lists.ÀŠÀŠ:::[@fmt=yyy@]: optional, yyy = ÀŠ:::::[@bygroup@]:default, level 1 list entries for each group with level 2 list entries for each page of a groupÀŠ:::::[@simple@]:one line per page, using full pagename: "* groupname.pagename", no group headersÀŠ:::::see also: Cookbook:DictIndexÀŠÀŠ:::[@list=zzz@]: optional, zzz = ÀŠ:::::[@normal@]:don't include special pages like [@RecentChanges@], [@GroupHeader@] and [@GroupFooter@] in the listÀŠÀŠ->You can do ÀŠ-->[@(:pagelist:)@] to get a list of all pages, ÀŠ-->[@(:pagelist group=PmWiki:)@] to get a list of all pages in the PmWiki group,ÀŠ-->[@(:pagelist group={$Group}:)@] to get a list of all pages in the current groupÀŠ-->[@(:pagelist group={$Group} list=normal:)@] to get a list of all pages in the current group except [@GroupHeader, GroupFooter, RecentChanges @] etcÀŠÀŠ->from mailings:ÀŠÀŠ-->For `RecentPages, I just put the following in my local/config.php:ÀŠ-->(There must be two spaces between the wikilink and the following text -> Copy&Paste from the source, not html view.)ÀŠÀŠ--->[@$RCTime = strftime('%b %d %H:%M',$Now);@]ÀŠ--->[@$RecentChangesFmt['Main.RecentPages'] = ':[[$FullName]]:  $RCTime';@]ÀŠÀŠÀŠ->see also:Cookbook:SearchResultsÀŠÀŠ[[#searchbox]][@(:searchbox:)@]ÀŠ->Shows a search box at this position.ÀŠÀŠ[[#searchresult]][@(:searchresults group=xxx fmt=yyy list=zzz text:)@]ÀŠÀŠ->see also:Cookbook.SearchResultsÀŠÀŠ[[#markup]][@(:markup:) [=...=]@]ÀŠ->Can be used for markup examples, showing first the markup and then the result of the markup. see PmWiki.TextFormattingRules for examples.ÀŠ->æœ€åˆã«ãƒãƒ¼ã‚¯ã‚¢ãƒƒãƒ—ã‚’è¡¨ç¤ºã—ã€æ¬¡ã«ãƒãƒ¼ã‚¯ã‚¢ãƒƒãƒ—ã®çµæœã‚’è¡¨ç¤ºã—ã¦ã€ãƒãƒ¼ã‚¯ä»˜ã‘ã®ä¾‹ã«ä½¿ç”¨ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ãŒã§ãã¾ã™ã€‚ä¾‹ã¯PmWikiJa.TextFormattingRulesã‚’è¦‹ã¦ãã ã•ã„ã€‚ÀŠÀŠ%trail%<<|[[PmWikiJa.ãƒ‰ã‚­ãƒ¥ãƒ¡ãƒ³ãƒˆç›®æ¬¡]]|>>
